<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 4:13<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I266c3570630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>4.</label.designator><headtext>Constitutional Privileges</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f53e7682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>4:13.</label.designator><headtext>Search and seizure—Warrant requirement</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>All persons enjoy the privilege against unreasonable search <page no="123"/>and seizure of their person and property under the Fourth Amendment of the United States Constitution. <eos/><bos/>The Georgia Constitution[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2ede3807fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] and the Georgia Code[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2ee0a907fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] provide similar protections.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Both federal and state law prefer searches be pursued under a valid search warrant, yet even in warranted searches evidence might be excluded due to a defect in the issuance or execution of the warrant itself.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2ee0a917fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] For example, a search warrant is invalid where it does not state with particularity items to be seized. <eos/><bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018126" w-serial-number="2041759842" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ifba420a27fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Bryant v. State,</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2ee0a927fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court found that a warrant is invalid where it lists only a description and an address of the home to be searched but does not provide a list of items to be seized even where a basis exists for procuring the warrant.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Both the United States and Georgia Constitutions require probable cause for the issuance of a warrant which is more than more than mere suspicion but less than “proof beyond a reasonable doubt.”[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2ee0a937fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] To obtain a warrant, <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“[t]here need only be probable cause to believe that evidence of a crime has been secreted on specific premises. <eos/><bos/>Probable cause exists where the facts and circumstances would warrant a man of reasonable caution in believing that the evidence sought is in the place described.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2ee0a947fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>] If a warrant is obtained pursuant to an affidavit based on information from a confidential informant, the magistrate must independently determine the reliability of the information and the informant.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2ee31a07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018126" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST17-5-21" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ifba691a07fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 17-5-21</cite.query> sets forth the grounds for issuance of a search warrant. <eos/><bos/>Further, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018126" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="ES" w-normalized-cite="GAST17-15-22" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ifba691a17fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. §§ 17-15-22</cite.query> to <cite.query w-src-number="0287018126" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="ES" w-normalized-cite="GAST17-15-28" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ifba691a27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">17-15-28</cite.query> provide the statutory framework for the application, issuance, and execution of search warrants.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>With respect to evidentiary practice, practitioners should file a motion to suppress if a <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“search and seizure with a warrant was illegal because the warrant is insufficient on its face, there was not probable cause for the issuance of the warrant, or the warrant was illegally executed”<end.quote refid="QT_0002"/> within the scope of the Georgia Code or the state or federal constitutions.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2ee31a17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">8</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>However, be aware that when a search warrant affidavit contains incorrect information, and the court concludes that if <page no="124"/>that information is set aside the affidavit still contains sufficient facts to establish probable cause, then the search conducted pursuant to the warrant is lawful.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2ee31a27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">9</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic2ede3807fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018126" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GACNART1S1PXIII" w-pub-number="1000469" ID="Ifba29a007fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Ga. Const. 1983, Art. I, § I, ¶ XIII</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2ee0a907fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Title 17, Ch.5, Art. II.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2ee0a917fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018126" w-serial-number="2004152842" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ifba384627fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Groh v. Ramirez, 540 U.S. 551, 124 S. Ct. 1284, 157 L. Ed. 2d 1068 (2004)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018126" w-serial-number="1984132648" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ifba384667fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Massachusetts v. Sheppard, 468 U.S. 981, 104 S. Ct. 3424, 82 L. Ed. 2d 737 (1984)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2ee0a927fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018126" w-serial-number="2041759842" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ifba46ec27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Bryant v. State, 301 Ga. 617, 800 S.E.2d 537 (2017)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2ee0a937fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018126" w-serial-number="1963125280" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ifba559227fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Wong Sun v. U.S., 371 U.S. 471, 479, 83 S. Ct. 407, 9 L. Ed. 2d 441 (1963)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2ee0a947fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Goger, Daniel&apos;s Georgia Criminal Trial Practice § 4:7 (2018-2019 ed.).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2ee31a07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018126" w-serial-number="2039438159" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ifba61c727fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Torres v. State, 338 Ga. App. 269, 789 S.E.2d 634 (2016)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2ee31a17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018126" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="ES" w-normalized-cite="GAST17-15-30" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ifba706d07fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 17-15-30(b)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="124"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2ee31a27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018126" w-serial-number="2030240050" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ifba77c027fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Charleston v. State, 292 Ga. 678, 743 S.E.2d 1 (2013)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 4:13<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
